From a production standpoint, Mr. Sebastian; could you please consider not rolling your camera before validating that you've got what what intended? Not a single contract as an IBM Subcontractor gets to move to opening boxes until this step is completed. If, after all these years, you've still not yet learned the lesson of "double-checking things" before bragging about what you're about to do, you're at this stage deliberately lying to your audience, because you know better. This is click bait, pure and simple, and you need to retire, because you're wasting people's time. I'd rather be Rick Rolled instead of hearing your excuses for why you can't plan, order and validate your hardware before turning on the camera!

snippet.textDisplay: I'm always asking myself who is buying these super expensive,  super high capacity enterprise server drives. I work in the IT department of large university / public research institute and while I'm not directly involved with data center operations I know we definitely aren't. We use a mixture of consumer and normal NAS drives with a capacity of 2, 4 and 8TB with 4TB being the most common and 2TB slowly being phased out. We don't really care about service and lifetimes even for consumer drives aren't bad. The real money here is spanned on the tape library which stores cold and archival data.
snippet.textOriginal: I'm always asking myself who is buying these super expensive,  super high capacity enterprise server drives. I work in the IT department of large university / public research institute and while I'm not directly involved with data center operations I know we definitely aren't. We use a mixture of consumer and normal NAS drives with a capacity of 2, 4 and 8TB with 4TB being the most common and 2TB slowly being phased out. We don't really care about service and lifetimes even for consumer drives aren't bad. The real money here is spanned on the tape library which stores cold and archival data.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's worth noting that l2arc is only caching what's getting evicted from the ARC, so building a full l2ARC is quite slow. And for now, l2ARC do not persist accross reboot. There is a pull request in review right now, as we are talking, but it's not availlable yet, and I exepect ZFS packages of various distros to lag a bit behind. So no persistant l2ARC for a while.
Another thing is that l2ARC is still taking some place in the ARC, storing some kind of table. I do not remember the numbers exactly, but an empty l2ARC in your case can still use severall Gigs, so be carefull with that.
